# Line-ending policy lives HERE, not in each developer's core.autocrlf.
#
# Why this file exists before any binary file does: ChronoTrace's whole product
# is a binary log format (.chrono). Git for Windows commonly installs with
# core.autocrlf=true, which rewrites LF -> CRLF on checkout. Applied to a binary
# recording, that silently corrupts every 0x0A byte in the file and the failure
# surfaces as an unreproducible CRC error weeks later.
#
# core.autocrlf is per-machine and does not travel with the repo. .gitattributes
# does. Adding it after the first .chrono fixture lands is too late: git has
# already normalised the blob on the way in.

# Normalise text in the repo to LF; check out LF everywhere (including Windows).
* text=auto eol=lf

# Never touch these. Any translation is corruption.
*.chrono binary
*.chrono.idx binary
*.zst binary
*.png binary
*.gif binary
*.jpg binary
*.ico binary
*.whl binary
